d and - of course - he said, he - he wasn't coming out of hospital 'til he'd got a glove - a stuffed glove, he wasn't going to walk about like that, a lad fifteen. Anyway he did come out - with - no fingers, he'd got a thumb, and he wrote with that part a
n
d the doctor learnt him - while he had got bandages on. He learnt him to write so he could use this - keep using this thumb - and he's working today, with no fingers on his hand. And he works to Johnson and Matthes, Burslem. I don't know exactly what he d
o
es, something with photography you see, but he is working, he can work and - earn his own living. He was a placer then, you know, but - when he first started back again but - all these years he's never got married. He's always been sensitive to this and I
 
keep telling him he's foolish, mores the pity. That's right, you see, when he puts his left hand - his right hand to shake he says anybody - it goes through 'em when they shake hands. I said, oh they get used to it. No, but - he's wrong like that you know
. Yes, yes, that's right. This is - this is a thing that upset him anyway. So that's Douglas.
