 for other people. It's their way of - well this is just a thing that is happened, not that I'm bi
goted, far from it, because - I mean I'd pay for any - for anybody it it was - that's one thing I don't like. People going and won't let you pay. I don't like that. Especially - you know very well that they can't afford it, you see, and they kind of pay f
o
r five or six different people together. Well, I think it's wrong to expect them to pay for you. My way of thinking anyway. Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, I do. And if anybody does anything for me - I try to repay 'em another way. Same as this - you see - Nurse Dadd
ocks'll say, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid816496\charrsid9981595 Else}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
, will you do me such a thing? Yes. Are you going to make any marmalade? Yes. Oh well you - make me some while you're at it you know, and these are the things that - you know, I think to myself, well it's one good turn, she's very good to m
e and she watches me up and if there's anything - I want, even me pension or anything, she'd fetch it. 'Cos some days I don't feel as though I can walk up the street, never mind - 'course when I got to the bank this is where it does me. That is me heart o
f course I know but - this is it, I keep going along the best I can. So is there anything - you really want, I mean, don't -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 When you were at home all the children more or less had a job to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yours was if your mother was taking in washing you were doing the ironing?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 If she was out with a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
If she was out with a confinement she would help with the cooking and things like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Yes. The other's'd help just they same, they'd have to do, me dad'd see to that. That they'd 
help, you know, in any jobs that want doing say - hasn't got it time, you must do such a thing before I come home from work, you know, and this was it. Oh yes, he used to see that while me mother was out you know, this was - what she'd do, but - although 
m
e mother - was out with these sort of cases a lot - she didn't get paid for it as regards money. She used to get it back in kind. You see. Different things for us. You see, this is how they used to pay her. Is by giving - or if we were short of anything y
ou know they'd say - oh well, I'll get that, don't get it, I'll get - you know, and see as you had what - you know. This is how things used to - turn out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
There weren't sort of health visitors in those days, it was a neighbourhood thing that a competent woman would go out and help the other women in childbirth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Well - we didn't bring them in the world or anything of this. I mean, there was a midwife. There was a midwife as couldn't go out for - without a doctor. And there was a - and there'd be a 
certified midwife. So as regards that - me mother used to go out to different cases, both those that are having the doctor as well and - but it was to - same as me - to do a good turn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 You obviously learnt some of this service to others from your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Yes. That's right. And - now I was quite surprised when I was - just told - I'd be about twenty-three, I was about six years and I hadn't got a house, I was going from different rooms you know, in different rooms. And I lived with a person - who 
was very old and I'd got me two boys at the same time, they used to be very miserable with the children you know but they weren't with me. And - I used to go in and I used to wash the old man, it was an old man you see, he was very - poorly and that. He u
s
ed - when he was off side and - if he had - what we - said, oh he said, I've been a choking, and I'd run in you know. And I'd say come on dad, arms up. And I'd put his hands on the door - come on, and I'd rub his - between his shoulder and that. And - I'd
 
been in and I've washed him, and I've stripped him to the waist and I was only twenty-three, I hadn't done any nursing then or anything. And - I was quite surprised, I'd left there, I'd been left there about twelve months and there came - somebody come ru
n
ning up our - I forget who the errand runner was at the time, Elsie - Grandad Pointon's very ill, will you come. Grandma wants you come at once. And her says, she says, I don't know, she says, but I think he's dead. You know. So of course I went at once a
n
d come back - but you know what she wanted me to do? What I - she shouted me for? Lay her husband out. And I was twenty-three. She'd got daughters fifty-six. That was the first time I ever did anything. And it was an old man. I'll never forget it. And I w
e
nt home and - oh I sobbed me heart out 'til children come out of school. And - said what's up mum? And I said, nothing - why? You know, making it straight. He said is your eyes red, is me dad bad again? You see. So I said, no duck. I said, do you know you
r
 granddad Pointon? Said, yes. I said, well - he's died. Our Bill - he picked - he was washing his hands ready for his tea - eldest lad - hurray, he threw the sponge up in the air - that's; what they thought of their granddad. Here I was breaking me heart 
over it. And - that -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Do you remember how you felt about being punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Well we knew we'd done wrong of course - we had to go to bed, we had to put up with it you know. Parents were always right really. We thought - that any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Would you
 say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents, or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
No. No, I don't - I think both of them played their part very well really. 'Course we saw more of mother, for t
he the simple reason that dad - worked and - he used to take us a walk Sunday - Sunday afternoons and - Sunday mornings he used to take the little ones out you know. But we always used to take - he used to be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 So he used to take you out for walks on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Yes. When we was at home he would, in the afternoons. He'd go out for a drink Sunday nights you know - we didn't go very far Sunday nights, of course the younger ones'd be in bed and - perhaps I'd be at church and Polly'd be at church as wel
l. Only two of us'd be church you know and then he would go out. He had used to go along to the club on Sundays, the working mens club. But he never come the worse for drink or anything. If - a good time that he would come in - he'd had a little extra he 
w
ould - drink he'd come and he'd just lie on the sofa and go to sleep, he wasn't a rowdy man at all. And - me mother used to go when I come out of church and etcetera, used to go to him about - half past nine, just for the last half hour And - she'd have j
u
st a drink then then they'd come back, they wouldn't go again 'til the following weekend. You see this is one reason I think that - drink never troubled me. I never - been one as has had any alcohol and I wouldn't thank anybody for it now. If ever I - I l
i
ke the company, I'm not saying as I don't like - the company in a public hours or club or anything, I do, I love the company, but if I went - say we'd got company and they all had a drink, I would only have either an orangeade or - a ginger beer. And if m
other and father, they used to have half a pint of beer me mother would have, he'd have perhaps have a pint, perhaps two pints. He never went much farther.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Not much, only that we had a birthday card from me mum and dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 You'd get your birthday card regularly but there wasn't cash for presents?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 No. No, not - no parties or anything of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Can you remember anything you did with your mother and father together at Chri
stmas, Could you describe a Christmas that you had while you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Well we all had - the stockings filled of course, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid816496\charrsid9981595 oranges}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
, apples, nuts - we always used to have that, and one small present. Such as a - for a toy like - something - 
where I would probably have - I was bigger - box handkerchiefs or something of that, they always used to try to keep these things away 'til Christmas. Then we would - all sit round cracking nuts and walnuts another, making a proper mess of the house to be
 
cleaned up and - me mum and dad always used to share it with us, you know, they - me father was passionately fond of nuts and he used to - sit there cracking new nuts you know, and he could eat as many as he broke. And - me mother, then at night time we h
ad a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid816496\charrsid9981595 harmonica}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
, not a piano or anything of that - and - while we were little used to begin pom pom with one finger, never - and - very often if me father's brother came down - this was mostly Sundays that he came, or Christmas time, he used to come down and
 he used to play the harmonium and we used to sit round the table you know singing to it, hymns and etcetera. Well, at Christmastime we were allowed partly to do anything regards - which would give us enjoyment. Me father let me pom pom on and he wouldn't
 
kind of go - no, this was it. We - had pretty well our liberty in our day and that such as - picnicking in the summer holidays, Christmas holidays, same as I say we were allowed pretty well in the house. And we would allow - be allowed to do things in the
 house, where normally - it had got to be tidied up and - everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Some extra efforts would be made for Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
This is what was - yes, she used to make a big - seven pound jam jar and she'd do these ready for Christmas and put them awa
y in a - it used to go up the far end of the pantry, you know, we shouldn't know what that was. When we used to fetch things out, say - fetch the sugar our or jam out or - out of the pantry, we'd go out and we wouldn't think of looking thereon the shelf, 
w
e wouldn't know what was on there you know. Oh she made homemade mince pies and things like this you know. Mince was the same. She used to - make her mince - she'd go - well what shall I say, say you went for - apples, things like that you know, she would
n
't know what this was. And she'd make a seven pound jar - a big stone jar they were at that time, and she'd make perhaps; put currants and etcetera in you know, and she would make a seven pound jar of that to see us through Christmas. If there was more - 
a
s long as it lasted we had it you know, she baked and we had what there was. But - always, didn't matter what it was, we always had a fair share. In everything. Although sometimes we would say, oh can't I have another piece, and say, no, you've had enough
 
for tonight. You're having no more, it'll leave some for tea tomorrow. You know, she'd perhaps do four or five tarts, mince tarts, and she'd cut 'em up - and when we'd had what she thought we'd had enough you know she'd leave it. She'd say, no, I'm not cu
t
ting in another one, that's for tomorrow. And same as if she'd make pies. Same as I said when she went up on Mondays to make - see what meet her could get you know, and she did this potted meat, sometimes she'd do lobby for Tuesday and - she'd buy - boil 
-
 boil up all the meat in it you know and save part of the gravy and - the meat, half of the meat, and she'd make a meat and potato pie ready for the next day, Wednesday, and this is how she used to do. Plan her meals, very well - over the money she'd got 
y
ou know. No, I think she did, I think she was a good - for the food, I mean we never went short of a meal. I don't ever remember us - I couldn't go in and have a piece of jam if nothing else. Just dry bread and jam probably you know but - I never remember
 
ever going - in strikes even - when my father was out of work, the same as I say the food kitchens I described to you on - before - we - used to have that you know, but I never remember actually going without a meal and being hungry. And this is another t
hing that I think about these foreigners as go hungry, if people'd only think of other people a little bit. They throw quite a lot away which I've seen thrown away. And - but - that they would be glad of, you know, if they could put it to a better use.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Would you be able to have chicken or pork or something on Christmas Day?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes. Yes, we would have a chicken or something of that on Christmas Day.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 You said you had this harmonium that your dad used to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Could your mum play as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Nobody could play it, it was one of me grandmother's as was handed down you know. None of us learned to play or anything. We had used to have this half hour we used to say community hymn singing, I very often think about it when it's on the -
 the radio you know. This again - I mean - memories to look back on although - when I think you know we didn't have much of a life as regards - but we enjoyed them. Same as I say about cleaning shoes for somebody and having a penny for cleaning three pair
s
 and - that was a bit extra pocket money. But mother didn't take that off us, you see. But she probably wouldn't let - if I'd done something of the sort of me brother had done something of the sort, cleaned shoes or run errands, and we'd been given so muc
h for doing them you know - she's say, well, you won't want anything, you've already got that as you've just been spent it like, leave that much for the other, she'd give them perhaps a toffee or something of that you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 So nobody in the family bel
onged to bands or anything like that, apart from the harmonium there weren't any other musical instruments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Not in the house. But - me brothers - they had a - so many years ago I've forgot - what they're called - me brother that had his fingers off, he played - come a little further I call it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 The trombone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Yes. And me other - older brother than him, George, he used to be in the Scouts and he used to play and instrument but - I never - you know then - I was older and I hadn't used to take that much interest you know in what they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Fairly regularly you used to sing with your dad round this harmonium?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Did you parents play games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 What kind of games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Shakes and ladders. Dominoes. Things
 like that you know. And my father would give the young ones a ride on his back around the table you know and go round the table with the young ones playing and - hide - hide and seek and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 A fairly happy family life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
