Well, various time really. Now, some days he would go six o'clock and come home for breakfast or dinner, or if he took it with him, which is sometimes the case you know - that - he would probably come home about four o'clock, if - they'd done so m
uch work, you see, if they'd placed the oven to a certain extent or there's some-times that they'd got plenty of work to go on with to start placing and they would carry on 'til about six o'clock. But it used to vary from four 'til six. Now, if they didn'
t
 finish the oven, you see, and they got there next morning it means that - the oven would be behind all the time you know, because the firing would have been going on through the night if they could have finished it. If they'd got to go next morning to do
 
perhaps two hours work then it - it was waste of time, this was when - you know, it turned another whole day. They can start the fires up, yes, but - It means so long before they can get it - started - the oven started. Same as I say, it would be all oven
 - bottle necked ovens that me father worked in and these - big wash stands and etcetera, it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13589634\charrsid9981595 heavy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595  work. But - sometimes he'd be - there should be occasions when he'd have to go and do perhaps two or three hours and the other one hasn't cooled down enou
gh, the other oven you see, so he couldn't go only just those few hours. He'd be free them time, you know, he'd come home and he'd perhaps help to do a bit of decorating or something of that, whatever - wanted doing you know.
