\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
What would you have said they were if you had to describe them, working class people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Yes. Working class people and - the nobility. The bit better educated, they've been able to afford - different things which we weren't, you know, able to get. Definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Which class would you say you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Working class always. Poor class.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
What sort of people belonged to this class, the sort of people you were living among, people with biggish families and low wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Well - ar regards this I don't know - we're not all big family - they hadn't all got big families 
but - I happened to belong to one that - were a big family. 'Course not - same as I say, not fourteen of us that were living because - but it was a big family for all that. These jobs had got to be done. But - I - I belonged to the poorer class I know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 No, never. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 You weren't taught to curtsey or touch your cap or show respect in some way?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 We - had to do that with a poor class or the
 nobility. We were always brought up - same as receiving prizes from Sunday school, we were supposed to curtsey and the boys salute when they received a prize. And - if you met anyone in the street that you knew, such as your teacher, or anything of this,
 
the boys always saluted the teacher, and we always - good morning or - time of the day. Anyone that we knew you know - we were always expected to speak but not - run after 'em or make a fuss because it's teacher or anything, morning Miss Johnson or good m
orning Mr - Mr Such a body you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 In the district where you lived who were considered the most important people?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
I don't know. We hadn't any - what I would say very important people. They were - a distance away, same as - Mr Sidney Malkin and 
- people like him, this is - these are people that had got the money and would put up for councils or something of that you know, but - I don't remember anybody really, you know, even us teachers and the - the headmasters and all that, and the ministers, 
w
e'd always show respect for. I can't understand children of today there isn't any - manners really or anything, you don't see anybody - even say hallo to them much, you know - people that they know and they just absolutely ignore. Or ask how they are, you
 
don't get people - you know, to do these things. If you see, it - they'd say now, oh they're devils here, if he happened to touch his cap for anything, which I have a friend - well I haven't now, he died about two month ago - down the road here, and he ne
v
er met me in the street but what he didn't touch his cap and he'd stand back to - and he was much older than me, but he'd stand back for me get on the bus before him and he would try to help me - on the bus. You find none of that curtsey at all now, that 
we had to show. Why, if our parents had have seen us get on a bus or anything before an elderly person they'd have gone wild.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
The important people like Mr Malkin didn't live round about so you didn't come into contact with them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 How would you have rated shopkeepers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
The working - working class like us, be people like ourselves. But it was their job of work, same as us going to work with our jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 The clergy and teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes. Kind of - a bit - a little - not much but - m
e mother wouldn't mind you. The made their children to respect - yes, respect their elders and also respect officials like teachers and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Did you think there were different kinds of people who went to church from those who went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 No. No. NO, we didn't think anything of that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Where you lived did all the people in the working classes have the same standard of living or would you say they were different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Well I don't say different groups, but there was different circum
stances shall I say. We were - I never found any - different groups as I can say groups at all because we always seemed to be - I used to reckon myself as good as anyone else, I might as well be truthful, and my parents brought me up in the best way they 
could and this is what I thought, I was as good as the next, now - I hadn't got the money but we were brought up decent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Did you think that any group did see itself as superior, were there some people who worked in the potteries who thought they had jobs that made them better than the rest of the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Made them superior like, oh yes, you do find different people, you do today as regards that but - there were higher people that - did think they were higher up than you but - I never used to think
 that of them you know, I didn't - there was some people as thought they could domineer probably over you but - being brought up as I'd got to curtail and not answer 'em back in everything that was what I thought was right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 This would be on their standard of living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes. The behaviour of the - the children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Well, no, - not t
hat I know of. I mean - I've always been brought up on the factor what I've worked you know but what - I know I don't know anyone. Of course there's the bosses always that are higher than you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 But pre-1918 you weren't particularly conscious of this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Pre-19 - yes. Conscious of the - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Well to my way of thinking they did, I can't say any different you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Do you think your mother saw herself as be
longing to any particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Would she have said she was working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 She would have said she was a working class woman, nothing else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 This would come because your dad was working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Was a working class - had to work for his living.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Was it possible at this time for people to move from one class to another?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
No, I don't think it would. This never entered me head thinking anybody'd be ever any different - to me. I don't think so anyway. Kind of the working class and they're always working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 You can't remember anybody who sort of made good?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Not any individual, not as I can - mention. 'Because same as - I've just told - I've told you all long ours was - a home life, family life, we didn't g
o out much, you know, to - we went out play and all this but we - I don't remember anyone, you know, putting up for anything as - and he'd reached the top or anything of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Oh yes. In - in different - people. It is so in ours - our family. The bringing up we had as regards strictly bringing up, yes, but - there's different ones that I could mention as regard that if - you met them you know, well - he's a proper gentlema
n, he would help a lame dog over a stile and - and he wouldn't think anything about it you know, and he's respectful in his talk, both to children and adults, you know. Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. His conduct.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
Oh - I did. We played with - one of me friends was a policeman - his - child - child was anyway, his girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
What did you think of him, did your mother used to threaten you with the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 No, they never threatened us 
with the police or anything as regards that, me father's wasn't a threat. He thought I could talk to a policeman because I'd - he'd always brought up as a - we'd been brought up that a policeman was supposed to respect anybody's - con - you know - he was 
s
upposed to be that was said from a policeman, only what had got to go in a court of law, you know. He was good to children - what was his name now - Sutcliffe - Bobby Sutcliffe we used to call - I did have one occasion and by all that I've told you you wi
l
l know now the - other side of me. This Mrs Rolley that was my mother's friend, she let me one day to look after the son. And also - to - see that - the kettle and everything was boiling for masters tea when he came in. I did these jobs and she says, I've
 left yours and Frank's tea on the - side there ready for you and you must stop and have your tea with Frank and then when Mr Rolley comes he'll look to Frank. 'Course this again - I looked to him, I saw he was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13589634\charrsid9981595 washed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595  before his dad come home from work and 
he'd had his tea and his father's tea was what I thought was ready. But - I'd - put tea out and I'd done same as I do at home, equal share. And for this tea there was a tin of fruit which she'd opened and put in a dish and I'd have put as much for Frank a
n
d as much for his father and as much for myself all round. I'd - I'd divided it three ways. And - 'course at night time when his wife come back home - says - do you like your lady, she says to me mother. She says, why, what's the matter? She says, used al
l that tin of fruit. Her says - weren't a bit left for me when I got home. I says - I don't know what sort of tea they had, her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13589634\charrsid9981595  says, but - Frank said he hadn
\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595  got enough. So that must have been a home where the father had the biggest bulk, but this is wha
t I'd done of course, and she was expecting to have some left, you see. So of course me mother put it down - told - shouted me in and she said - me mother put it as good as I was stealing. And she said to me she said, now if you don't tell me the truth, s
h
e says, I shall take you up to Mr Sutcliffe. And - I told you the truth mum. She says, well where did all that stuff go? I said, we eat it between us. And then me mother realized, you know, after I'd told her, I said, I should - Mrs Rolley said it was on 
t
he side for me and I'd got to put it out like, I said, that what's I done. Said, oh well, you must have had a good tea. I said, yes, I did have a good tea mum, I said, and I ate more bread and butter than Mr Rolley - Mrs - Frankie Rolley like, I said, but
 
- I didn't steal anything. And of course, she says, if you don't I shall fetch - if you don't tell me the truth unless he's - what I always said, the only - one and only time that they ever threatened me with the police, and this was because this Mrs Roll
e
y had said, you know, as good as said I'd stole her tea kind of style. But oh I broke my heart and I said, oh don't tell Mr Sucliffe, don't tell him, this was the truth you know and as I'd told her, I said, but I can go and tell Mr Sutcliffe if - if you w
ant me to, I said, but - don't let their Maggie be in. You know, this was the way, I would go up to him and tell him but - this woman was so - so kind of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13589634\charrsid9981595 
scrappy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 , if she went for buy tomatoes or anything of that for their take she'd always ask for small one
s you see and she'd - make 'em last kind of understand. Same as my mother did to a certain extent, but she said that was our tea, and that is what I did. Yes. But this was it you know and that has always stuck in my mind about police. You know. And honest
l
y now although I knew people were in the wrong I've had a little carry on here which made me very ill a few weeks ago, about a boy having a gun and I knew - the girl as had been shot the night - the day before, it - the pellet came out of her neck and - d
o you know, that was on my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13589634\charrsid9981595 conscience}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 
 ever - in fact, I even asked the minister to come here, I wanted to talk to him, it was making me bad, getting me nerves worked up and he said, Mrs Tinsley, if I went for the police and ask them come in plain clothes wi
ll you tell them this? And - I said, oh I couldn't. I said, I would go anywhere and tell 'em but not a policeman come to our house. You know, and it does, make me really ill when I've got anything on my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13589634\charrsid9981595 conscience}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595  like that. And this, you see, it's not man
y months ago round here that this happened. And that was - same as I say - perhaps the reason the policeman, you know - now we never - get - put a policeman - I'd sooner hit a boy and then them summons me for it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2889289 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Yes. Three and six a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid469682 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11499485\charrsid9981595 Did you see anything of the landlord?
